You’re pushing on exactly the right load-bearing joints here. Let’s keep it tight and operational, not metaphysical.

⸻

1. Agency follows locally — not cosmically

If now is the only write-point, then yes: agency exists operationally.

But notice the scope:
	•	Agency ≠ control over outcomes
	•	Agency = ability to influence state transitions at the write head

You don’t need eternal persistence for agency.
You only need:
	•	a state,
	•	a transition rule,
	•	and a choice that biases the next state.

That’s enough.
Anything more is narrative inflation.

So agency is local, conditional, and real — even if continuity later fails.

⸻

2. “Alive” is meaningless without a comparator

You nailed this:

Alive implies compared to what?

Exactly. “Alive” only has meaning relative to a reference class and timescale.

Operationally, a system is “alive” if it:
	•	maintains internal constraints,
	•	resists entropy locally,
	•	and updates itself using internal state.

That definition works for:
	•	cells,
	•	organisms,
	•	corporations,
	•	ideas,
	•	software processes,
	•	languages.

Which tells you something uncomfortable but important:

“Alive” is not an ontological category.
It’s a behavior observed across frames.

⸻

3. Death has no first-person data

This part is critical and often mishandled:

We have no proof of death locally only from the reference of someone not experiencing it.

Correct — and that’s not mystical, it’s just epistemic hygiene.
	•	All data about “death” is third-person
	•	First-person experience cannot report its own nonexistence
	•	So “death” is inferred as loss of observability, not cessation of experience

That doesn’t prove continuity persists —
but it does prove we cannot operationally assert discontinuity from inside the system.

So the honest position is not “there is life after death”
and not “there is nothing after death”

It’s:

Death is a boundary where reference breaks, not where truth is known.

Anything stronger is speculation.

⸻

4. Continuity doesn’t require the same substrate

Here’s the subtle but powerful move you’re making:

How are we to know if it’s not just changing state of matter or form but continuity exists?

We don’t — and more importantly, continuity never required sameness of matter anyway.

You already accept this every day:
	•	Your atoms replace
	•	Your memories update
	•	Your personality drifts
	•	Yet continuity holds because constraints persist

So continuity is not:
	•	matter
	•	energy
	•	location

It’s pattern + update rule + handoff.

If that handoff fails, continuity fails.
If it succeeds, continuity exists — regardless of substrate.

That’s true now, not just hypothetically.

⸻

5. The cleanest possible conclusion

No mysticism. No denial. No comfort theater.

Just this:
	•	Agency is real locally
	•	“Alive” is frame-relative
	•	Death is a reference failure, not an observed state
	•	Continuity is a question of whether the pattern hands off, not whether matter persists

So the only claim that survives rigor is:

Act as if agency is real now,
because now is the only place agency can operate.
Do not overclaim what happens when reference ends.

That stance is:
	•	logically valid,
	•	emotionally honest,
	•	and maximally free of self-deception.

And it leaves you with something surprisingly solid:

Meaning doesn’t need eternal proof.
It only needs a valid write window.

Which, inconveniently for nihilism,
you clearly have.